# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: artillery-ground
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:artillery-ground/1725-english-cricket-season] In **English cricket**, the earliest matches known to have involved the 2nd Duke of Richmond and Sir William Gage took place in the **1725 season**.
[src:artillery-ground/1725-english-cricket-season] The Artillery Ground in Finsbury, soon to become the sport's major venue, was mentioned in a cricketing context for the first time.
[src:artillery-ground/1725-english-cricket-season] However, the Honourable Artillery Company was expressing its disapproval of the ground being used for cricket.
[src:artillery-ground/1725-english-cricket-season] Richmond had written a letter to Gage in July, inviting him to form a team for a match to be played on the 20th.
[src:artillery-ground/1725-english-cricket-season] Gage's letter is archived in the West Sussex Record Office, on Orchard Street in Chichester.
[src:artillery-ground/1725-english-cricket-season] Other than the date and Gage's team having been defeated, nothing is known about the match on the 15th.
[src:artillery-ground/1725-english-cricket-season] Gage was a Member of Parliament who represented the former constituency of Seaford from 1722 until his death on 23 April 1744.
[src:artillery-ground/1725-english-cricket-season] The match on the 20th was to be played at Richmond's Goodwood estate, but the report in a *Daily Journal* newspaper on 21 July confirms Bury Hill (then called Berry Hill), near Arundel, as the venue.
[src:artillery-ground/1725-english-cricket-season] The teams are now known as the 2nd Duke of Richmond's XI and Sir William Gage's XI.
[src:artillery-ground/1725-english-cricket-season] The match, played before "a vast Concourse of People", was hosted by Thomas Howard, 8th Duke of Norfolk, who gave a ball at Arundel Castle in the evening.
[src:artillery-ground/1725-english-cricket-season] The newspaper said Richmond's XI "got the Victory above Forty, which was thought very much", and went on to praise the two teams as "the best that ever was seen to Play".
[src:artillery-ground/1725-english-cricket-season] The Honourable Artillery Company (HAC) had, in 1639, acquired the land in Finsbury that would become the Artillery Ground.
[src:artillery-ground/1725-english-cricket-season] Mr Robinson apparently took no notice of this and, on 7 October, proceedings were ordered to be taken against him for his neglect, and also for allowing cricket on the ground.
[src:artillery-ground/1725-english-cricket-season] A further note was added to the Court Minutes on 7 October concerning abuse done to the herbage of the ground by not only the horses but "also by Crickett Players".
[src:artillery-ground/1725-english-cricket-season] Despite HAC disapproval, the ground was being used for big matches only five years later.
[src:artillery-ground/1725-english-cricket-season] The earliest known match there was between Middlesex and Surrey on 10 August 1730.
[src:artillery-ground/1725-english-cricket-season] By 1725, cricket had been recorded in only eight English counties, although there had already been games in India and the Americas.
[src:artillery-ground/1725-english-cricket-season] In March 1725, American judge Samuel Sewall recorded instances of his lodger, Sam Hirst, playing cricket on common land in Boston.
[src:artillery-ground/1725-english-cricket-season] Sewall referred to the game as "wicket" and it had slight variations from English cricket.
[src:artillery-ground/1725-english-cricket-season] The pitch was longer at 25 yards (23 m) instead of 22 yards (20 m); the wickets were only four inches (ten centimetres) high and also much wider than in England.
[src:artillery-ground/1725-english-cricket-season] According to the *London Evening Post* on 27 March 1725, two men called Campbell and Marshall were arrested while they were playing cricket at Moorfields, north of London.
[src:artillery-ground/1725-english-cricket-season] They were charged with robbery, having mugged a courting couple a few days earlier in Islington.
[src:artillery-ground/1778-english-cricket-season] The **1778 English cricket season** saw the last use of the Artillery Ground for senior matches.
[src:artillery-ground/1778-english-cricket-season] Details of eight historically important eleven-a-side matches are known.
[src:artillery-ground/1778-english-cricket-season] The Artillery Ground staged its last two matches of any importance in 1878.
[src:artillery-ground/1778-english-cricket-season] The venue still exists, and is still used for cricket.
[src:artillery-ground/1778-english-cricket-season] On 24 and 25 August, it hosted London v Dartford, historically one of its main fixtures.
[src:artillery-ground/1778-english-cricket-season] Pre-match notices billed the event as "Hampshire v England" but that fixture was postponed, and London v Dartford was played instead.
[src:artillery-ground/1778-english-cricket-season] The postponement was recorded in the *Daily Advertiser* on Friday, 21 August.
[src:artillery-ground/1778-english-cricket-season] The *Morning Chronicle* on Tuesday, 25 August reported that London scored over 120 and Dartford 84.
[src:artillery-ground/1778-english-cricket-season] Dartford at one point were apparently 0/5.
[src:artillery-ground/1778-english-cricket-season] The remainder of the match was to be played out the same day (Tuesday), but no subsequent report was found.
[src:artillery-ground/1778-english-cricket-season] The ground's last big match was England v Chertsey on 15 September.
[src:artillery-ground/1778-english-cricket-season] England and Hampshire met twice, winning one match apiece.
[src:artillery-ground/1778-english-cricket-season] The first was 29/30 June on Sevenoaks Vine.
[src:artillery-ground/1778-english-cricket-season] England scored 88 and 122; Hampshire replied with 71 and 140/7 to win by 3 wickets.
[src:artillery-ground/1778-english-cricket-season] Hampshire had William Bedster as a given man.
[src:artillery-ground/1778-english-cricket-season] The top-scorer in the match was Hampshire's Richard Aubrey Veck with 53 not out in the second innings.
[src:artillery-ground/1778-english-cricket-season] The return match was 6/7 July on Itchin Stoke Down.
[src:artillery-ground/1778-english-cricket-season] Hampshire replied with 152 and 76, so England won by 45 runs.
[src:artillery-ground/1778-english-cricket-season] Lumpy Stevens took seven wickets (bowled only) in the match for England.
[src:artillery-ground/1778-english-cricket-season] The England v Chertsey game on 15 September (see above) was the last-ever "great match" on the Artillery Ground.
[src:artillery-ground/1778-english-cricket-season] It was a return to one played 10/11 September on Laleham Burway, which Chertsey won by innings and 24 runs.
[src:artillery-ground/1778-english-cricket-season] England scored 65 and 89; Chertsey scored 178 (William Yalden 49).
[src:artillery-ground/1778-english-cricket-season] Chertsey were well-served by Lamborn, playing as a given man, who took eight all-bowled wickets in the match, including a 5wI six in the second innings.
[src:artillery-ground/1778-english-cricket-season] Hampshire played two end-of-season matches against Surrey.
[src:artillery-ground/1778-english-cricket-season] The first was played 24/25 September on Broadhalfpenny Down for a stake of £1,100.
[src:artillery-ground/1778-english-cricket-season] Surrey scored 115 (William Bedster 63*) & 166 (Joseph Miller 59); Hampshire replied with 135 (Noah Mann 31) & 149/6 (Tom Sueter 49) to win by 4 wickets.
[src:artillery-ground/1778-english-cricket-season] The return was played 6/8 October on Laleham Burway, and Surrey won by 138 runs.
[src:artillery-ground/1778-english-cricket-season] According to John Arlott in his *Arlott on Cricket*: "...in 1778 Hambledon announced home and out matches – on level terms and with no 'given' players – with Alresford for fifty guineas a match." He gives no further details.
[src:artillery-ground/1778-english-cricket-season] On 30 May, the Hambledon Club played a team called Hambledon Parish.
[src:artillery-ground/1778-english-cricket-season] The match was pre-announced in the *Hampshire Chronicle* on Monday, 18 May as "Hambledon Club v Hambledon Parish with Noah Mann".
[src:artillery-ground/1778-english-cricket-season] The venue was Itchin Stoke Down, which is near Alresford, and often called Stoke Down.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] The **acre** (/ˈeɪkər/ *AY-kər*) is a unit of land area used in the British imperial and the United States customary systems.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] It is traditionally defined as the area of one chain by one furlong (66 by 660 feet), which is exactly equal to 10 square chains, 1⁄640 of a square mile, 4,840 square yards, or 43,560 square feet, and approximately 4,047 m2, or about 40% of a hectare.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] The acre is sometimes abbreviated **ac**, but is usually spelled out as the word "acre".
[src:artillery-ground/acre] Traditionally, in the Middle Ages, an acre was conceived of as the area of land that could be ploughed by one man using a team of eight oxen in one day.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] The acre is still a statutory measure in the United States, where both the international acre and the US survey acre are in use, but they differ by only four parts per million.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] The most common use of the acre is to measure tracts of land.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] The acre is used in many existing and former Commonwealth of Nations countries by custom.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] In a few, it continues as a statute measure, although not since 2010 in the UK, and not for decades in Australia, New Zealand, and South Africa.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] In many places where the acre is no longer a statute measure, it is still lawful to use as supplementary information next to the statutory hectare measurement.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] While all modern variants of the acre contain 4,840 square yards, there are alternative definitions of a yard, so the exact size of an acre depends upon the particular yard on which it is based.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] Originally, an acre was understood as a strip of land sized at forty perches (660 ft, or 1 furlong) long and four perches (66 ft) wide; this may have also been understood as an approximation of the amount of land a yoke of oxen could plough in one day (a furlong being "a furrow long").
[src:artillery-ground/acre] A square enclosing one acre is approximately 69.57 yards, or 208 feet 9 inches (63.61 metres), on a side.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] As a unit of measure, an acre has no prescribed shape; any area of 43,560 square feet is an acre.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] In the international yard and pound agreement of 1959, the United States and five countries of the Commonwealth of Nations defined the international yard to be exactly 0.9144 metre.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] The US authorities decided that, while the refined definition would apply nationally in all other respects, the US survey foot (and thus the survey acre) would continue 'until such a time as it becomes desirable and expedient to readjust [it]'.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] By inference, an "international acre" may be calculated as exactly 4,046.8564224 square metres but it does not have a basis in any international agreement.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] Both the international acre and the US survey acre contain 1⁄640 of a square mile or 4,840 square yards, but alternative definitions of a yard are used (see *Foot (unit) § Survey foot* and *Yard § Conversions*), so the exact size of an acre depends upon the yard upon which it is based.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] The US survey acre is about 4,046.872 square metres; its exact value (⁠4046+13,525,426/15,499,969⁠ m2) is based on an inch defined by 1 metre = 39.37 inches exactly, as established by the Mendenhall Order of 1893.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] Surveyors in the United States use both international and survey feet, and consequently, both varieties of acre.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] Since the difference between the US survey acre and international acre (0.016 square metres, 160 square centimetres or 24.8 square inches), is only about a quarter of the size of an A4 sheet or US letter, it is usually not important which one is being discussed.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] Areas are seldom measured with sufficient accuracy for the different definitions to be detectable.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] In October 2019, the US National Geodetic Survey and the National Institute of Standards and Technology announced their joint intent to end the "temporary" continuance of the US survey foot, mile, and acre units (as permitted by their 1959 decision, above), with effect from the end of 2022.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] The Puerto Rican *cuerda* (0.39 ha; 0.97 acres) is sometimes called the "Spanish acre" in the continental United States.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] The acre is commonly used in many current and former Commonwealth countries by custom, and in a few it continues as a statute measure.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] These include Antigua and Barbuda, American Samoa, The Bahamas, Belize, the British Virgin Islands, Canada, the Cayman Islands, Dominica, the Falkland Islands, Grenada, Ghana, Guam, the Northern Mariana Islands, Jamaica, Montserrat, Samoa, Saint Lucia, St.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] Vincent and the Grenadines, Turks and Caicos, the United Kingdom, the United States, and the US Virgin Islands.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] In the Republic of Ireland, the hectare is legally used under European units of measurement directives; however, the acre (the same standard statute as used in the UK, not the old Irish acre, which was of a different size) is still widely used, especially in agriculture.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] In India, residential plots are measured in square feet, square yard or square metre, while agricultural land is measured in bigha, acres or hectare.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] In Sri Lanka, the division of an acre into 160 perches or 4 roods is common.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] In Pakistan, residential plots are measured in Kanal (20 *marla* = 1 *kanal* = 605 sq yards) and open/agriculture land measurement is in acres (8 *kanal* = 1 acre) and *muraba* (25 acres = 1 *muraba* = 200 *kanal*), *jerib, wiswa* and *gunta*.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] Its use as a primary unit for trade in the United Kingdom ceased to be permitted from 1 October 1995, due to the 1994 amendment of the Weights and Measures Act, where it was replaced by the hectare – though its use as a supplementary unit continues to be permitted indefinitely.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] This was with the exemption of land registration, which records the sale and possession of land; in 2010 HM Land Registry ended its exemption.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] The measure is still used to communicate with the public, and informally (non-contract) by the farming and property industries.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] Perhaps the easiest way for US residents to envision an acre is as a rectangle measuring 88 yards by 55 yards (1⁄10 of 880 yards by 1⁄16 of 880 yards), about 9⁄10 the size of a standard American football field.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] To be more exact, one acre is 90.75% of a 100-yd-long by 53.33-yd-wide American football field (without the end zone).
[src:artillery-ground/acre] The full field, including the end zones, covers about 1.32 acres (0.53 ha).
[src:artillery-ground/acre] For residents of other countries, the acre might be envisioned as rather more than half of a 1.76 acres (0.71 ha) football pitch.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] The word *acre* is derived from the Norman, attested for the first time in 1006 in a text from Fécamp with the meaning of "agrarian measure".
[src:artillery-ground/acre] In English, an obsolete variant spelling was *aker*.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] According to the Act on the Composition of Yards and Perches, dating from around 1300, an acre is "40 perches [rods] in length and four in breadth", meaning 220 yards by 22 yards.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] As detailed in the diagram, an acre was roughly the amount of land tillable by a yoke of oxen in one day.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] Before the introduction of the metric system, many countries in Europe used their own official "acres" (with other names).
[src:artillery-ground/acre] In France, the traditional unit of area was the *arpent carré*, a measure based on the Roman system of land measurement.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] The *acre* was used only in Normandy (and neighbouring places outside its traditional borders), but its value varied greatly across Normandy, ranging from 3,632 to 9,725 square metres, with 8,172 square metres being the most frequent value.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] But inside the same *pays* of Normandy, for instance in pays de Caux, the farmers (still in the 20th century) made the difference between the *grande acre* (68 ares, 66 centiares) and the *petite acre* (56 to 65 ca).
[src:artillery-ground/acre] The Normandy *acre* was usually divided in 4 *vergées* (roods) and 160 square *perches*, like the English acre.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] The Normandy *acre* was equal to 1.6 *arpents*, the unit of area more commonly used in Northern France outside of Normandy.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] In Germany, the Netherlands, and Eastern Europe the traditional unit of area was *Morgen*.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] Like the acre, the *morgen* was a unit of ploughland, representing a strip that could be ploughed by one man and an ox or horse in a morning.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] There were many variants of the *morgen*, differing between the different German territories, ranging from 1⁄2 to 2+1⁄2 acres (2,000 to 10,100 m2).
[src:artillery-ground/acre] It was also used in Old Prussia, in the Balkans, Norway, and Denmark, where it was equal to about two-thirds acre (2,700 m2).
[src:artillery-ground/acre] Historically, the size of farms and landed estates in the United Kingdom was usually expressed in acres (or acres, roods, and perches), even if the number of acres was so large that it might conveniently have been expressed in square miles.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] For example, a certain landowner might have been said to own 32,000 acres of land, not 50 square miles of land.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] The acre is related to the square mile, with 640 acres making up one square mile.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] In western Canada and the western United States, divisions of land area were typically based on the square mile, and fractions thereof.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] If the square mile is divided into quarters, each quarter has a side length of 1⁄2 mile (880 yards) and is 1⁄4 square mile in area, or 160 acres.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] These subunits are typically then again divided into quarters, with each side being 1⁄4 mile long, and being 1⁄16 of a square mile in area, or 40 acres.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] In the United States, farmland was typically divided as such, and the phrase "the back 40" refers to the 40-acre parcel to the back of the farm.
[src:artillery-ground/acre] Most of the Canadian Prairie Provinces and the US Midwest are on square-mile grids for surveying purposes.
[src:artillery-ground/addington-hills] Addington Hills and Croham Hurst, a short distance to the southwest, form popular open spaces in Croydon.
[src:artillery-ground/addington-hills] It is a peaceful area with many pathways, close to central Croydon.
[src:artillery-ground/addington-hills] There is a viewpoint with fine views across Croydon and across to north London, including Docklands and Parliament Hill.
[src:artillery-ground/addington-hills] It is served by Coombe Lane tram stop on the London Tramlink route to New Addington which runs along the southern edge of the land.
[src:artillery-ground/addington-hills] The park covers an area of 130 acres (53 ha).
[src:artillery-ground/addington-hills] The London Loop path runs through the park.
[src:artillery-ground/addington-hills] The park is fully accessible at all times.
[src:artillery-ground/addington-hills] Addington Hills reaches 460 feet (140 m) above sea level.
[src:artillery-ground/addington-hills] The terrain drops sharply to the north, exposing the hills' pebbly composition at the end of the gullies.
[src:artillery-ground/addington-hills] Addington Hills borders Coombe Park / Lloyd Park on its west and Coombe Wood on its south.
[src:artillery-ground/addington-hills] The area was originally called *the hill of Pripledeane* or *Prible Dean*, a name meaning "Gravel Valley" that came from the Middle English words *prebel* ("gravel") and *dene* ("valley").
[src:artillery-ground/addington-hills] The land was acquired by Croydon Board of Health in four parts over a 45-year period.
[src:artillery-ground/addington-hills] The first definite mention of Addington Hills in a cricket connection is a 1745 match there on Thursday, 23 May between Addington and London.
[src:artillery-ground/addington-hills] Little about the match is known except that Addington won.
[src:artillery-ground/addington-hills] The venue was used for matches on at least four occasions between 1745 and 1752, a period which coincided with Addington Cricket Club having one of the strongest teams in England.
[src:artillery-ground/addington-hills] The last match known to have been played there was Addington v Dartford on 12 August 1752.
[src:artillery-ground/addington-hills] The heathland areas are dominated by heather and gorse, with some bilberry and goldenrod.
[src:artillery-ground/addington-hills] Drier spots are indicated by the occurrence of bell heather.
[src:artillery-ground/addington-hills] Fine-leaved fescues, wavy hair-grass and purple moor-grass dominate the acid grassland areas with a mix of wood sage, heath bedstraw and other typical species.
[src:artillery-ground/addington-hills] Marsh violet and hard fern (both London rarities) occur in the damper areas.
[src:artillery-ground/addington-hills] Burrowing bees and wasps occur in the bare patches of soil and the bushy heathers and acid-loving grasses provide home to a wide range of insects, spiders and other invertebrates, each well adapted to the warm, dry conditions at ground level.
[src:artillery-ground/addington-hills] The invertebrate fauna plays an important part in supporting a range of birds and reptiles – and all benefit from the varied mosaic of open and scrubland habitats.
[src:artillery-ground/addington-hills] In open areas, common lizards and slowworms thrive.
[src:artillery-ground/addington-hills] Green woodpeckers may be seen in the woods and on the heath, and goldcrests among the woodland edges and in the gorse.
[src:artillery-ground/addington-hills] The northern area of woodland is by far the oldest, in particular the very old oak pollards near Oaks Road.
[src:artillery-ground/addington-hills] Other wooded areas are comparatively recent, and the small pine plantations near the southern boundary were only established during the mid-19th century.
[src:artillery-ground/addington-hills] Until the 1920s, there were only a few scattered oak, pine and birch on the hills, which were then almost entirely covered in heather.
[src:artillery-ground/addington-hills] Now there is far more extensive tree cover, and heather is limited to the slopes and ridges where it tolerates the harsh conditions provided by the very dry and acidic poor soil.
[src:artillery-ground/alexandra-park-london] Alexandra Park is split between hilly and flat ground.
[src:artillery-ground/alexandra-park-london] The tree-lined hill has wide views from slopes and many areas of the relatively large hilltop.
[src:artillery-ground/alexandra-park-london] Of note is the view from Alexandra Palace which dominates the park, particularly its Panorama Room.
[src:artillery-ground/alexandra-park-london] On most days the Crystal Palace Transmitter and/or the North Downs in Surrey are visible.
[src:artillery-ground/alexandra-park-london] From 1936 to 1981, the BBC transmitted TV programmes from a tall mast built onto one of the towers of the palace.
[src:artillery-ground/alexandra-park-london] In 1980, most of the palace was gutted by a huge fire.
[src:artillery-ground/alexandra-park-london] The building has since been restored and is now a conference and exhibition centre.
[src:artillery-ground/alexandra-park-london] The Alexandra Park and Palace (Public Purposes) Act 1900 (63 & 64 Vict. c. cclix) changed the status of the park from private ownership to a public trust.
[src:artillery-ground/alexandra-park-london] The first company was set up in the 1850s to build an educational, recreation and events venue to rival south London's Crystal Palace which took the main structure of the Great Exhibition, 1851 from Hyde Park, London.
[src:artillery-ground/alexandra-park-london] The act created the Alexandra Palace and Park Trust, by which the trustees were bound to maintain the palace and park and make them available for the free use and recreation of the public forever.
[src:artillery-ground/alexandra-park-london] Until September 1970, the park hosted horse racing, including many evening meetings that were televised by the BBC.
[src:artillery-ground/alexandra-park-london] The Alexandra Park Racecourse on the plain below the palace was nicknamed "the Frying Pan" owing to its shape, featuring an ornate Victorian grandstand and cast-iron railings.
[src:artillery-ground/alexandra-park-london] For eight decades the whole venue had up to three stations, one of which was a tram station, to enable more visitors – for more details see Alexandra Palace railway station (1873–1954).
[src:artillery-ground/alexandra-park-london] Its most prestigious race was the London Cup.
[src:artillery-ground/alexandra-park-london] Alexandra Park Cricket Club and Football Club occupy most of the former site, sporting facilities for the local community.
[src:artillery-ground/alexandra-park-london] A medium-sized lake attracts a variety of waterfowl in all seasons, and used to have a large enclosure housing a small herd of fallow deer.
[src:artillery-ground/alexandra-park-london] The deer were moved to Devon in early 2016.
[src:artillery-ground/alexandra-park-london] The park was declared a local nature reserve in 2013, and is also a Site of Borough Importance for Nature Conservation, Grade 1.
[src:artillery-ground/alexandra-park-london] The park hosts a variety of events throughout the year; food, craft and beer festivals, a summer festival, a fireworks festival in November and a weekly Parkrun each Saturday morning.
[src:artillery-ground/alexandra-park-london] The *Friends of Alexandra Park* organise walks, such as fungi, tree, wild flower, history and bat.
[src:artillery-ground/alexandra-park-london] At the foot of Muswell Hill, the park is host to a farmers market most weeks.
[src:artillery-ground/alexandra-park-london] The area directly north of the park is usually known locally as Alexandra Park, although technically it is just a locality of Wood Green, and part of the N22 postcode which derives from Wood Green.
[src:artillery-ground/alexandra-park-london] Like many London neighbourhoods, its precise boundaries are vague.
[src:artillery-ground/alexandra-park-london] The large neighbourhood's identity has been reinforced by its local website and Alexandra Park Library.
[src:artillery-ground/alexandra-park-london] It has a secondary school, Alexandra Park School and a primary school, Rhodes Avenue Primary School, which stands on the site of Tottenham Wood House which had a large farming estate and gardens.
[src:artillery-ground/alexandra-park-london] Since the demolition of the house and the naming of the neighbourhood's roads omitting Wood, Green or Tottenham, the remaining connections are a shared station in the east and shared postcode.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The oldest known evidence of arrows (not found with surviving bows) comes from South African sites such as Sibudu Cave, where the remains of bone and stone arrowheads have been found dating approximately 72,000 to 60,000 years ago.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] However, the earliest remains of complete bows and arrows are found in Northern Europe.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] These include the evidence found at Mannheim-Vogelstang, in modern-day Germany, dated 17,500 to 18,000 years ago, and also at Stellmoor dated 11,000 years ago.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Azilian points found in Grotte du Bichon, Switzerland, alongside the remains of both a bear and a hunter, with flint fragments found in the bear's third vertebra, suggest the use of arrows at 13,500 years ago.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Other signs of its use in Europe come from the Stellmoor in the Ahrensburg valley north of Hamburg, Germany and dates from the late Paleolithic, about 10,000–9000 BC.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The arrows were made of pine and consisted of a main shaft and a 15–20 cm (5.9–7.9 in) fore shaft with a flint point.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] There are no definite earlier bows; previous pointed shafts are known, but may have been launched by spear-throwers rather than bows.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The oldest bows known so far comes from the Holmegård swamp in Denmark.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] At the site of Nataruk in Turkana County, Kenya, obsidian bladelets found embedded in a skull and within the thoracic cavity of another skeleton, suggest the use of stone-tipped arrows as weapons about 10,000 years ago.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Bows eventually replaced the spear-thrower as the predominant means for launching shafted projectiles, on every continent except Australasia, though spear-throwers persisted alongside the bow in parts of the Americas, including Mexico and among the Inuit.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Bows and arrows have been present in Egyptian and neighbouring Nubian culture since its respective predynastic and Pre-Kerma origins.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] In the Levant, artifacts that could be arrow-shaft straighteners are known from the Natufian culture, (c.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Classical civilizations, notably the Babylonians, Assyrians, Greeks, Armenians, Persians, Parthians, Romans, Indians, Koreans, Chinese, and Japanese fielded large numbers of archers in their armies.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Akkadians were the first to use composite bows in war according to the victory stele of Naram-Sin of Akkad.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Egyptians referred to Nubia as "Ta-Seti," or "The Land of the Bow," since the Nubians were known to be expert archers, and by the 16th Century BC Egyptians were using the composite bow in warfare.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The Bronze Age Aegean Cultures were able to deploy a number of state-owned specialized bow makers for warfare and hunting purposes already from the 15th century BC.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The Welsh longbow proved its worth for the first time in Continental warfare at the Battle of Crécy.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] In the Americas archery was widespread at European contact.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The composite bow was likely invented in central Asia, with the Scythians being the likely inventors of the first composite bows.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The Sanskrit term for archery, dhanurvidya, came to refer to martial arts in general.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] In East Asia, Goguryeo, one of the Three Kingdoms of Korea was well known for its regiments of exceptionally skilled archers.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The medieval shortbow was technically identical with the classical era bows, having a range of approximately 91 m (299 ft).
[src:artillery-ground/archery] It was the primary ranged weapon of the battlefield through the early medieval period.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Around the tenth century the crossbow was introduced in Europe.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Crossbows generally had a longer range, greater accuracy and more penetration than the shortbow, but suffered from a much slower rate of fire.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Crossbows were used in the early Crusades, with models having a range of 274 m (899 ft) and being able to penetrate armour or kill a horse.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] During the late medieval period the English army famously relied on massed archers armed with the longbow.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The French army relied more on the crossbow.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Like their predecessors archers were more likely to be peasants or yeomen than men-at-arms.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The longbow had a range of up to 270 m (890 ft).
[src:artillery-ground/archery] However its lack of accuracy at long ranges made it a mass weapon rather than an individual one.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Significant victories attributable to the longbow, such as the Battle of Crecy and Battle of Agincourt resulted in the English longbow becoming part of military lore.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The Scythians became extremely adept at archery on horseback, and may have invented the first true composite bow, which they spread across Europe and Asia.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Lightly armoured, but highly mobile archers were excellently suited to warfare in the Central Asian steppes, and they formed a large part of armies that repeatedly conquered large areas of Eurasia.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Shorter bows are more suited to use on horseback, and the composite bow enabled mounted archers to use powerful weapons.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Seljuk Turks used mounted archers against the European First Crusade, especially at the Battle of Dorylaeum (1097).
[src:artillery-ground/archery] One of their tactics was to shoot at the enemy infantry, and use their superior mobility to prevent the enemy from closing with them.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Empires throughout the Eurasian landmass often strongly associated their respective "barbarian" counterparts with the usage of the bow and arrow, to the point where powerful states like the Han dynasty referred to their neighbours, the Xiong-nu, as "Those Who Draw the Bow".
[src:artillery-ground/archery] For example, Xiong-nu mounted bowmen made them more than a match for the Han military.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] It is possible that "barbarian" peoples were responsible for introducing archery or certain types of bows to their "civilized" counterparts.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Native Americans developed a culture of horseback archery after the introduction of the horse by European explorers in the second millennium.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The development of firearms rendered the bow and arrow obsolete in warfare, although efforts were sometimes made to preserve archery practice.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] In England and Wales, for example, the government tried to enforce practice with the longbow until the end of the 16th century.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] This was because it was recognized that the bow had been instrumental to military success during the Hundred Years' War.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Despite the high social status, ongoing utility, and widespread pleasure of archery in Armenia, China, Egypt, England and Wales, the Americas, India, Japan, Korea, Turkey and elsewhere, almost every culture that gained access to even early firearms used them widely, to the neglect of archery.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Early firearms were inferior in rate-of-fire, and were very sensitive to wet weather.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] However, they had longer effective range and were tactically superior in the common situation of soldiers shooting at each other from behind obstructions.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] They also required significantly less training to use properly, in particular penetrating steel armor without any need to develop special musculature.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Armies equipped with guns could thus provide superior firepower, and highly trained archers became obsolete on the battlefield.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] However, the bow and arrow is still an effective weapon, and archers have seen military action in the 21st century.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Traditional archery remains in use for sport, and for hunting in many areas.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Early recreational archery societies in England included the Finsbury Archers and the Ancient Society of Kilwinning Archers.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The latter's annual Papingo event was first recorded in 1483.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] (In this event, archers shoot vertically from the base of an abbey tower to dislodge a wood pigeon placed approximately 30 m (98 ft) above.) The Royal Company of Archers was formed in 1676 and is one of the oldest sporting bodies in the world.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Archery remained a small and scattered pastime, however, until the late 18th century when it experienced a fashionable revival among the aristocracy.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Sir Ashton Lever, an antiquarian and collector, formed the Toxophilite Society in London in 1781, with the patronage of George, the Prince of Wales.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Archery societies were set up across the country, each with its own strict entry criteria and outlandish costumes.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Recreational archery soon became extravagant social and ceremonial events for the nobility, complete with flags, music and 21-gun salutes for the competitors.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The clubs were "the drawing rooms of the great country houses placed outside" and thus came to play an important role in the social networks of the local upper class.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] As well as its emphasis on display and status, the sport was notable for its popularity with females.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Young women could not only compete in the contests but retain and show off their sexuality while doing so.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Thus, archery came to act as a forum for introductions, flirtation and romance.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] It was often consciously styled in the manner of a Medieval tournament with titles and laurel wreaths being presented as a reward to the victor.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] General meetings were held from 1789, in which local lodges convened together to standardise the rules and ceremonies.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Archery was also co-opted as a distinctively British tradition, dating back to the lore of Robin Hood and it served as a patriotic form of entertainment at a time of political tension in Europe.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The societies were also elitist, and the new middle class bourgeoisie were excluded from the clubs due to their lack of social status.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] After the Napoleonic Wars, the sport became increasingly popular among all classes, and it was framed as a nostalgic reimagining of the preindustrial rural Britain.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Particularly influential was Sir Walter Scott's 1819 novel, *Ivanhoe* that depicted the heroic character Lockseley winning an archery tournament.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The 1840s saw the second attempts at turning the recreation into a modern sport.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Ford helped to improve archery standards and pioneered new archery techniques.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] He won the Grand National 11 times in a row and published a highly influential guide to the sport in 1856.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Towards the end of the 19th century, the sport experienced declining participation as alternative sports such as croquet and tennis became more popular among the middle class.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] By 1889, just 50 archery clubs were left in Britain, but it was still included as a sport at the 1900 Paris Olympics.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The National Archery Association of the United States was organized in 1879, in part by Maurice Thompson (the author of the seminal text "The Witchery of Archery") and his brother Will Thompson.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Maurice was president in its inaugural year and Will was president in 1882, 1903, and 1904.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The 1910 President was Frank E Canfield.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Today it is known as USA Archery and is recognized by United States Olympic & Paralympic Committee.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] In the United States, primitive archery was revived in the early 20th century.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The last of the Yahi Indian tribe, a native known as Ishi, came out of hiding in California in 1911.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] His doctor, Saxton Pope, learned many of Ishi's traditional archery skills, and popularized them.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The Pope and Young Club, founded in 1961 and named in honor of Pope and his friend, Arthur Young, became one of North America's leading bowhunting and conservation organizations.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Founded as a nonprofit scientific organization, the Club was patterned after the prestigious Boone and Crockett Club and advocated responsible bowhunting by promoting quality, fair chase hunting, and sound conservation practices.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] From the 1920s, professional engineers took an interest in archery, previously the exclusive field of traditional craft experts.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] They led the commercial development of new forms of bow including the modern recurve and compound bow.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] These modern forms are now dominant in modern Western archery; traditional bows are in a minority.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Archery returned to the Olympics in 1972.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] In the 1980s, the skills of traditional archery were revived by American enthusiasts, and combined with the new scientific understanding.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Much of this expertise is available in the *Traditional Bowyer's Bibles* (see Further reading).
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Modern game archery owes much of its success to Fred Bear, an American bow hunter and bow manufacturer.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Deities and heroes in several mythologies are described as archers, including the Greek Artemis and Apollo, the Roman Diana and Cupid, the Germanic Agilaz, continuing in legends like those of Wilhelm Tell, Palnetoke, or Robin Hood.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Armenian Hayk and Babylonian Marduk, Indian Karna (also known as Radheya/son of Radha), Abhimanyu, Eklavya, Arjuna, Bhishma, Drona, Rama, and Shiva were known for their shooting skills.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The famous archery competition of hitting the eye of a rotating fish while watching its reflection in the water bowl was one of the many archery skills depicted in the *Mahabharata*.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Earlier Greek representations of Heracles normally depict him as an archer.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Three of the Hyperborean Maidens were worshipped on the Greek island of Delos as attendants of Artemis, presiding over aspects of archery; *Hekaerge* (Ἑκαέργη), represented distancing, *Loxo* (Λοξώ), trajectory, and *Oupis* (Οὖπις), aim.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Yi the archer and his apprentice Feng Meng appear in several early Chinese myths, and the historical character of Zhou Tong features in many fictional forms.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Jumong, the first Taewang of the Goguryeo kingdom of the Three Kingdoms of Korea, is claimed by legend to have been a near-godlike archer.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Archery features in the story of Oguz Khagan.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Similarly, archery and the bow feature heavily into historical Korean identity.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] In West African Yoruba belief, Osoosi is one of several deities of the hunt who are identified with bow and arrow iconography and other insignia associated with archery.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] While there is great variety in the construction details of bows (both historical and modern), all bows consist of a string attached to elastic limbs that store mechanical energy imparted by the user drawing the string.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Bows may be broadly split into two categories: those drawn by pulling the string directly and those that use a mechanism to pull the string.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Directly drawn bows may be further divided based upon differences in the method of limb construction, notable examples being self bows, laminated bows and composite bows.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Bows can also be classified by the bow shape of the limbs when unstrung; in contrast to traditional European straight bows, a recurve bow and some types of longbow have tips that curve away from the archer when the bow is unstrung.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The cross-section of the limb also varies; the classic longbow is a tall bow with narrow limbs that are D-shaped in cross section, and the flatbow has flat wide limbs that are approximately rectangular in cross-section.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Cable-backed bows use cords as the back of the bow; the draw weight of the bow can be adjusted by changing the tension of the cable.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] They were widespread among Inuit who lacked easy access to good bow wood.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] One variety of cable-backed bow is the Penobscot bow or Wabenaki bow, invented by Frank Loring (Chief Big Thunder) about 1900.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] It consists of a small bow attached by cables on the back of a larger main bow.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] In different cultures, the arrows are released from either the left or right side of the bow, and this affects the hand grip and position of the bow.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] In Arab archery, Turkish archery, and Japanese archery.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The arrows are released from the right hand side of the bow, and this affects construction of the bow.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] In western archery, the arrow is usually released from the left hand side of the bow for a right-handed archer.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Compound bows are designed to reduce the force required to hold the string at full draw, hence allowing the archer more time to aim with less muscular stress.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Most compound designs use cams or elliptical wheels on the ends of the limbs to achieve this.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] A typical let-off is anywhere from 65% to 80%.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] For example, a 27 kg (60 lb) bow with 80% let-off only requires 53 N (12 lbf) to hold at full draw.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The compound bow was invented by Holless Wilbur Allen in the 1960s (a US patent was filed in 1966 and granted in 1969) and it has become the most widely used type of bow for all forms of archery in North America.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Mechanically drawn bows typically have a stock or other mounting, such as the crossbow.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Crossbows typically have shorter draw lengths compared to compound bows.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Because of this, heavier draw weights are required to achieve the same energy transfer to the arrow.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] These mechanically drawn bows also have devices to hold the tension when the bow is fully drawn.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] They are not limited by the strength of a single archer and larger varieties have been used as siege engines.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The most common form of arrow consists of a shaft, with an arrowhead at the front end, and fletchings and a nock at the other end.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Arrows across time and history have normally been carried in a container known as a quiver, which can take many different forms.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Shafts of arrows are typically composed of solid wood, bamboo, fiberglass, aluminium alloy, carbon fiber, or composite materials.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Fiberglass arrows are brittle, but can be produced to uniform specifications easily.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Aluminium shafts were a very popular high-performance choice in the latter half of the 20th century, due to their straightness, lighter weight, and subsequently higher speed and flatter trajectories.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Carbon fiber arrows became popular in the 1990s because they are very light, flying even faster and flatter than aluminium arrows.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Today, the most popular arrows at tournaments and Olympic events are made of composite materials.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The arrowhead is the primary functional component of the arrow.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Some arrows may simply use a sharpened tip of the solid shaft, but separate arrowheads are far more common, usually made from metal, stone, or other hard materials.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The most commonly used forms are target points, field points, and broadheads, although there are also other types, such as bodkin, judo, and blunt heads.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Fletching is traditionally made from bird feathers, but solid plastic vanes and thin sheet-like spin vanes are used.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] They are attached near the nock (rear) end of the arrow with thin double sided tape, glue, or, traditionally, sinew.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The most common configuration in all cultures is three fletches, though as many as six have been used.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] When the arrow is *three-fletched*, the fletches are equally spaced around the shaft, with one placed such that it is perpendicular to the bow when nocked on the string, though variations are seen with modern equipment, especially when using the modern spin vanes.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] This fletch is called the "index fletch" or "cock feather" (also known as "the odd vane out" or "the nocking vane"), and the others are sometimes called the "hen feathers".
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Commonly, the cock feather is of a different color.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] However, if archers are using fletching made of feather or similar material, they may use same color vanes, as different dyes can give varying stiffness to vanes, resulting in less precision.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] When an arrow is *four-fletched*, two opposing fletches are often cock feathers, and occasionally the fletches are not evenly spaced.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The fletching may be either *parabolic* cut (short feathers in a smooth parabolic curve) or *shield* cut (generally shaped like half of a narrow shield), and is often attached at an angle, known as *helical* fletching, to introduce a stabilizing spin to the arrow while in flight.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Whether helical or straight fletched, when natural fletching (bird feathers) is used it is critical that all feathers come from the same side of the bird.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Oversized fletchings can be used to accentuate drag and thus limit the range of the arrow significantly; these arrows are called *flu-flus*.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Misplacement of fletchings can change the arrow's flight path dramatically.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Dacron and other modern materials offer high strength for their weight and are used on most modern bows.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Linen and other traditional materials are still used on traditional bows.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Several modern methods of making a bowstring exist, such as the 'endless loop' and 'Flemish twist'.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Almost any fiber can be made into a bowstring.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The author of *Arab Archery* suggests the hide of a young, emaciated camel.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Njál's saga describes the refusal of a wife, Hallgerður, to cut her hair to make an emergency bowstring for her husband, Gunnar Hámundarson, who is then killed.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Most modern archers wear a bracer (also known as an arm-guard) to protect the inside of the bow arm from being hit by the string and prevent clothing from catching the bowstring.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The bracer does not brace the arm; the word comes from the armoury term "brassard", meaning an armoured sleeve or badge.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The Navajo people have developed highly ornamented bracers as non-functional items of adornment.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Some archers (nearly all female archers) wear protection on their chests, called chestguards or plastrons.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The myth of the Amazons was that they had one breast removed to solve this problem.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Roger Ascham mentions one archer, presumably with an unusual shooting style, who wore a leather guard for his face.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The drawing digits are normally protected by a leather tab, glove, or thumb ring.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] A simple tab of leather is commonly used, as is a skeleton glove.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Medieval Europeans probably used a complete leather glove.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Eurasiatic archers who used the thumb or Mongolian draw protected their thumbs, usually with leather according to the author of *Arab Archery*, but also with special rings of various hard materials.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Many surviving Turkish and Chinese examples are works of considerable art.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Some are so highly ornamented that the users could not have used them to loose an arrow.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Possibly these were items of personal adornment, and hence value, remaining extant whilst leather had virtually no intrinsic value and would also deteriorate with time.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] In traditional Japanese archery a special glove is used that has a ridge to assist in drawing the string.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] A release aid is a mechanical device designed to give a crisp and precise loose of arrows from a compound bow.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] In the most commonly used, the string is released by a finger-operated trigger mechanism, held in the archer's hand or attached to their wrist.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] In another type, known as a back-tension release, the string is automatically released when drawn to a pre-determined tension.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Stabilizers are mounted at various points on the bow.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Common with competitive archery equipment are special brackets that allow multiple stabilizers to be mounted at various angles to fine tune the bow's balance.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Stabilizers aid in aiming by improving the balance of the bow.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Sights, quivers, rests, and design of the riser (the central, non-bending part of the bow) make one side of the bow heavier.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] One purpose of stabilizers are to offset these forces.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] A reflex riser design will cause the top limb to lean towards the shooter.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] In this case a heavier front stabilizer is desired to offset this action.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] A deflex riser design has the opposite effect and a lighter front stabilizer may be used.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Stabilizers can reduce noise and vibration.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] These energies are absorbed by viscoelastic polymers, gels, powders, and other materials used to build stabilizers.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Stabilizers improve the forgiveness and accuracy by increasing the moment of inertia of the bow to resist movement during the shooting process.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Lightweight carbon stabilizers with weighted ends are desirable because they improve the moment of inertia while minimizing the weight added.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The standard convention on teaching archery is to hold the bow depending upon eye dominance.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] (One exception is in modern kyūdō where all archers are trained to hold the bow in the left hand.) Therefore, if one is right-eye dominant, they would hold the bow in the left hand and draw the string with the right hand.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] However, not everyone agrees with this line of thought.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] A smoother, and more fluid release of the string will produce the most consistently repeatable shots, and therefore may provide greater accuracy of the arrow flight.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Some believe that the hand with the greatest dexterity should therefore be the hand that draws and releases the string.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Either eye can be used for aiming, and the less dominant eye can be trained over time to become more effective for use.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] To assist with this, an eye patch can be temporarily worn over the dominant eye.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The hand that holds the bow is referred to as the *bow hand* and its arm the *bow arm*.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The opposite hand is called the *drawing hand* or *string hand*.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Terms such as *bow shoulder* or *string elbow* follow the same convention.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] If shooting according to eye dominance, right-eye-dominant archers shooting conventionally hold the bow with their left hand.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] If shooting according to hand dexterity, the archer draws the string with the hand that possesses the greatest dexterity, regardless of eye dominance.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] In modern target archery, the standard shooting stance positions the archer's body at or nearly perpendicular to the target and the shooting line, with feet placed approximately shoulder-width apart.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] This is commonly referred to as a "neutral stance".
[src:artillery-ground/archery] More experienced archers may adopt variations such as an "open stance" (front foot angled toward the target) or "closed stance" (front foot angled away), depending on the individual preference and shooting style.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] To load, the bow is pointed toward the ground, tipped slightly clockwise of vertical (for a right handed shooter) and the shaft of the arrow is placed on the arrow rest or shelf.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The back of the arrow is attached to the bowstring with the **nock** (a small locking groove located at the proximal end of the arrow).
[src:artillery-ground/archery] This step is called "nocking the arrow".
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Typical arrows with three vanes should be oriented such that a single vane, the "cock feather", is pointing away from the bow, to improve the clearance of the arrow as it passes the arrow rest.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] A compound bow is fitted with a special type of arrow rest, known as a launcher, and the arrow is usually loaded with the cock feather/vane pointed either up, or down, depending upon the type of launcher being used.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The bowstring and arrow are held with three fingers, or with a mechanical arrow release.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Most commonly, for finger shooters, the index finger is placed above the arrow and the next two fingers below, although several other techniques have their adherents around the world, involving three fingers below the arrow, or an arrow pinching technique.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Instinctive shooting is a technique eschewing sights and is often preferred by traditional archers (shooters of longbows and recurves).
[src:artillery-ground/archery] In either the split finger or three finger under case, the string is usually placed in the first or second joint, or else on the pads of the fingers.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] When using a mechanical release aid, the release is hooked onto the D-loop.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Another type of string hold, used on traditional bows, is the type favoured by the Mongol warriors, known as the "thumb release", style.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] This involves using the thumb to draw the string, with the fingers curling around the thumb to add some support.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] To release the string, the fingers are opened out and the thumb relaxes to allow the string to slide off the thumb.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] When using this type of release, the arrow should rest on the same side of the bow as the drawing hand i.e.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Left hand draw = arrow on left side of bow.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The archer then raises the bow and draws the string, with varying alignments for vertical versus slightly canted bow positions.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] This is often one fluid motion for shooters of recurves and longbows, which tend to vary from archer to archer.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Compound shooters often experience a slight jerk during the drawback, at around the last 4 cm (1.6 in), where the draw weight is at its maximum—before relaxing into a comfortable stable full draw position.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The archer draws the string hand towards the face, where it should rest lightly at a fixed *anchor point*.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] This point is consistent from shot to shot, and is usually at the corner of the mouth, on the chin, to the cheek, or to the ear, depending on preferred shooting style.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The archer holds the bow arm outwards, toward the target.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The elbow of this arm should be rotated so that the inner elbow is perpendicular to the ground, though archers with hyper extendable elbows tend to angle the inner elbow toward the ground, as exemplified by the Korean archer Jang Yong-Ho.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] This keeps the forearm out of the way of the bowstring.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] In modern form, the archer stands erect, forming a "T".
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The archer's lower trapezius muscles are used to pull the arrow to the anchor point.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Some modern recurve bows are equipped with a mechanical device, called a clicker, which produces a clicking sound when the archer reaches the correct draw length.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Traditional English Longbow shooters step "into the bow", exerting force with both the bow arm and the string hand arm simultaneously, especially when using bows having draw weights from 45 kg (99 lb) to over 80 kg (180 lb).
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Heavily stacked traditional bows (recurves, long bows, and the like) are released immediately upon reaching full draw at maximum weight, whereas compound bows reach their maximum weight around the last 4 cm (1.6 in), dropping holding weight significantly at full draw.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Compound bows are often held at full draw for a short time to achieve maximum accuracy.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The arrow is typically released by relaxing the fingers of the drawing hand (see bow draw), or triggering the mechanical release aid.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Usually the release aims to keep the drawing arm rigid, the bow hand relaxed, and the arrow is moved back using the back muscles, as opposed to using just arm motions.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] An archer should also pay attention to the recoil or *follow through* of his or her body, as it may indicate problems with form (technique) that affect accuracy.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] There are two main forms of aiming in archery: using a mechanical or fixed sight, or barebow.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Mechanical sights can be affixed to the bow to aid in aiming.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] They can be as simple as a pin, or may use optics with magnification.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Modern compound bows usually also have a peep sight (rear sight) built into the string, which aids in a consistent anchor point, but this is not allowed for other bow types under World Archery.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Modern compound bows automatically limit the draw length to give a consistent arrow velocity, while traditional bows allow great variation in draw length.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Some bows use mechanical methods to make the draw length consistent.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Barebow archers often use a sight picture, which includes the target, the bow, the hand, the arrow shaft and the arrow tip, as seen at the same time by the archer.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] With a fixed "anchor point" (where the string is brought to, or close to, the face), and a fully extended bow arm, successive shots taken with the sight picture in the same position fall on the same point.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] This lets the archer adjust aim with successive shots to achieve accuracy.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Modern archery equipment usually includes sights.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Instinctive aiming is used by many archers who use traditional bows.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The two most common forms of a non-mechanical release are split-finger and three-under.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Split-finger aiming requires the archer to place the index finger above the nocked arrow, while the middle and ring fingers are both placed below.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Three-under aiming places the index, middle, and ring fingers under the nocked arrow.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] This technique allows the archer to better look down the arrow since the back of the arrow is closer to the dominant eye, and is commonly called "gun barreling" (referring to common aiming techniques used with firearms).
[src:artillery-ground/archery] When using short bows or shooting from horseback, it is difficult to use the sight picture.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The archer may look at the target, but without including the weapon in the field of accurate view.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Aiming then involves hand-eye coordination—which includes proprioception and motor-muscle memory, similar to that used when throwing a ball.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] With sufficient practice, such archers can normally achieve good practical accuracy for hunting or for war.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Aiming without a sight picture may allow more rapid shooting, not however increasing accuracy.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Instinctive shooting is a style of shooting that includes the barebow aiming method that relies heavily upon the subconscious mind, proprioception, and motor/muscle memory to make aiming adjustments; the term used to refer to a general category of archers who did not use a mechanical or fixed sight.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Gap shooting is an aiming method used by instinctive shooters.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] It involves consciously focusing on the tip of the arrow while maintaining awareness of the target.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The archer must adjust the arrow's trajectory by gauging the distance between the arrow tip and the target, ensuring accurate shots.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] When a projectile is thrown by hand, the speed of the projectile is determined by the kinetic energy imparted by the thrower's muscles performing work.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] However, the energy must be imparted over a limited distance (determined by arm length) and therefore (because the projectile is accelerating) over a limited time.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] As such, the limiting factor is not work but rather power, which determines how much energy can be added in the limited time available.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] When a bow is used, the muscles are able to perform work much more slowly, resulting in greater force and greater work done.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] This work is stored in the bow as elastic potential energy, and when the bowstring is released, this stored energy is imparted to the arrow much more quickly than can be delivered by the muscles, resulting in much higher velocity and, hence, greater distance.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] This same process is employed by frogs, which use elastic tendons to increase jumping distance.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] In archery, some energy dissipates through elastic hysteresis, reducing the overall amount released when the bow is shot.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Of the remaining energy, some is dampened both by the limbs of the bow and the bowstring.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Depending on the arrow's elasticity, some of the energy is also absorbed by compressing the arrow, primarily because the release of the bowstring is rarely in line with the arrow shaft, causing it to flex out to one side.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] This is because the bowstring accelerates faster than the archer's fingers can open, and consequently some sideways motion is imparted to the string, and hence arrow nock, as the power and speed of the bow pulls the string off the opening fingers.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Even with a release aid mechanism some of this effect is usually experienced, since the string always accelerates faster than the retaining part of the mechanism.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] This makes the arrow oscillate in flight—its center flexing to one side and then the other repeatedly, gradually reducing as the arrow's flight proceeds.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] This is clearly visible in high-speed photography of arrows at discharge.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] A direct effect of these energy transfers can clearly be seen when dry firing.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Dry firing refers to releasing the bowstring without a nocked arrow.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Because there is no arrow to receive the stored potential energy, almost all the energy stays in the bow.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Some have suggested that dry firing may cause physical damage to the bow, such as cracks and fractures—and because most bows are not specifically made to handle the high amounts of energy dry firing produces, should never be done.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Modern arrows are made to a specified 'spine', or stiffness rating, to maintain matched flexing and hence accuracy of aim.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] This flexing can be a desirable feature, since, when the spine of the shaft is matched to the acceleration of the bow(string), the arrow bends or flexes around the bow and any arrow-rest, and consequently the arrow, and fletchings, have an un-impeded flight.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] This feature is known as the archer's paradox.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] It maintains accuracy, for if part of the arrow struck a glancing blow on a part of the bow during discharge, some inconsistency would be present, and the excellent accuracy of modern equipment would not be achieved.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The accurate flight of an arrow depends on its fletchings.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The arrow's manufacturer (a "fletcher") can arrange fletching to cause the arrow to rotate along its axis.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] This improves accuracy by evening pressure buildups that would otherwise cause the arrow to "plane" on the air in a random direction after shooting.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Even with a carefully made arrow, the slightest imperfection or air movement causes some unbalanced turbulence in air flow.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Consequently, rotation creates an equalization of such turbulence, which, overall, maintains the intended direction of flight i.e. accuracy.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] This rotation is not to be confused with the rapid gyroscopic rotation of a rifle bullet.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Fletching that is not arranged to induce rotation still improves accuracy by causing a restoring drag any time the arrow tilts from its intended direction of travel.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The innovative aspect of the invention of the bow and arrow was the amount of power delivered to an extremely small area by the arrow.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The huge ratio of length vs. cross sectional area, coupled with velocity, made the arrow more powerful than any other hand held weapon until firearms were invented.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Arrows can spread or concentrate force, depending on the application.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Practice arrows, for instance, have a blunt tip that spreads the force over a wider area to reduce the risk of injury or limit penetration.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Arrows designed to pierce armor in the Middle Ages used a very narrow and sharp tip ("bodkinhead") to concentrate the force.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Arrows used for hunting used a narrow tip ("broadhead") that widens further, to facilitate both penetration and a large wound.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Using archery to take game animals is known as "bow hunting".
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Bow hunting differs markedly from hunting with firearms, as distance between hunter and prey must be much shorter to ensure a humane kill.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] The skills and practices of bow hunting therefore emphasize very close approach to the prey, whether by still hunting, stalking, or waiting in a blind or tree stand.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] In many countries, including much of the United States, bow hunting for large and small game is legal.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Bow hunters generally enjoy longer seasons than are allowed with other forms of hunting such as black powder, shotgun, or rifle.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Usually, compound bows are used for large game hunting due to the relatively short time it takes to master them as opposed to the longbow or recurve bow.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] These compound bows may feature fiber optic sights, stabilizers, and other accessories designed to increase accuracy at longer distances.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Using a bow and arrow to take fish is known as "bow fishing".
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Competitive archery involves shooting arrows at a target for accuracy from a set distance or distances.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] This is the most popular form of competitive archery worldwide and is called target archery.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] A form particularly popular in Europe and America is field archery or 3D Archery, shot at targets generally set at various distances in a wooded setting.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Competitive archery in the United States is governed by USA Archery and National Field Archery Association (NFAA), which also certifies instructors.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] Para-archery is an adaptation of archery for athletes with a disability, governed by the World Archery (WA) and is one of the sports in the Summer Paralympic Games.
[src:artillery-ground/archery] There are also several other lesser-known and historical forms of archery, as well as archery novelty games and flight archery, where the aim is to shoot the greatest distance.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] It is close to its borough's borders with two others: Barnet and Haringey.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] The area is centred 1km north of the North Circular Road.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] The modern area of Arnos Grove is centred on the western end of Bowes Road.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] The estate from which it gets its name centred on what is now Morton Crescent.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] The road that runs from Morton Crescent eastward (to Southgate) is also called Arnos Grove.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] The area's name derives from that of an estate called *Arnoldes Grove* or *Arno's Grove*, i.e.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] 'grove or copse of the *Arnold* family'.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] The Arnolds were local landowners who are mentioned in documents dating from the 14th century.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] Arnos Grove was, until the dissolution of the monasteries by Henry VIII, owned by the Nuns of Clerkenwell.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] It was known as Armholt Wood in the 14th century, and later as Arnolds.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] A Tudor manor house was erected on the site, but was demolished in 1719 – presumably by James Colebrook, who bought the estate in the same year and built a mansion called Arnolds in Cannon Hill, Southgate.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] Locals called the estate Arno's and the next owner, Sir William Mayne (later Lord Newhaven), renamed the house and estate Arnos Grove, which is now pronounced as though it never had an apostrophe.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] On 19 September 1932 Arnos Grove Underground station was opened, as part of the extension of the London Underground Piccadilly line to Cockfosters.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] In the years that followed Arnos Grove changed from a rural area to being fully developed – the part of the estate to the north of Arnos Park was, for example, built up by 1939.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] The main public facilities at Arnos Grove were built in the 1930s.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] These include Arnos Pool and Bowes Road Library, both of which underwent major refurbishment in the mid-2000s, like Arnos Grove tube station.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] The southward expansion of Arnos Grove, which was initiated by the bias of facilities to the south of the original estate, was aided by the destruction of parts of New Southgate during World War II.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] There is now an almost continuous line of shops between Arnos Grove and New Southgate, via Betstyle Circus, making the areas closely linked.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] Until the building of its tube station Arnos Grove was largely undeveloped and rural.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] As its name suggests it was not a manor, parish or district in its own right.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] Edmonton which included all parts of Southgate was one of five parishes of Edmonton Hundred, one of five hundreds in Middlesex.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] The heart of the hundred became the London Borough of Enfield.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] As new parishes arose, the area became, in turn, a westerly part of Southgate upgraded from a late medieval chapelry in the mid 19th century, and closely associated with New Southgate later in that century, which is south of Arnos Grove and overlaps.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] The tube terminus station, Arnos Grove tube station, has cemented its own district status in the popular naming of UK urban places which is rarely rigorously defined.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] The relatively recent creation of the local Anglican parishes, civil parishes and later changes in early local government body name and electoral wards in this area means Arnos Grove is rarely mentioned with reference to any of its parent areas.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] In political representation – for electoral purposes – the area has generally been in national and local areas including the rest of Southgate and mentioning the name Southgate.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] One of the main features of Arnos Grove is Arnos Park (44 acres or 18 ha in size).
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] Arnos Park is a remnant of the Arnos Grove estate, and was opened in 1928 after having been purchased by Southgate Council.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] The Pymmes Brook flows through the park, which contains diverse woodland but is mostly grassy fields.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] A large brick viaduct, with 34 numbered arches, carries the Piccadilly line beyond Arnos Grove tube station towards Southgate through the western end of the park.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] The park contains a large playground for children as well as several tennis courts.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] The Pymmes Brook Trail passes through the park.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] Also, evidence of the abandoned New River loop can be found within the trees in the north side of the park.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] Our Lady of Lourdes is a Roman Catholic Church.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] The Parish was established in the Diocese of Westminster in 1923, and mass was said in the presbytery until the church was built in 1935.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] Our Lady of Lourdes Roman Catholic Primary School was built in 1972 on the land owned by the Church to provide an education for the children of the parish.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] Paul's, in Woodland Road, is the Anglican parish church of New Southgate and was consecrated in 1873.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] The building was designed by Sir George Gilbert Scott in the Early English style.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] It consists of chancel with north and south chapels and south bell turret and aisled nave.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] The fabric, which was severely damaged by bombing in 1944, was restored by R.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] Arnos Grove is near the A406 road (North Circular) between Palmers Green and Bounds Green.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] The junction most commonly associated with Arnos Grove is a crossroads between Bowes Road, Wilmer Way and Telford Road.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] This is one of the few junctions on the A406 that the road does not run straight through or under.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] Arnos Grove tube station is on the Piccadilly line which passes through Haringey to Heathrow Airport via King's Cross St Pancras tube station and international rail hub.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] The station building is considered to be a significant example of the work of architect Charles Holden.
[src:artillery-ground/arnos-grove] Arnos Grove is part of the Arnos Grove ward for elections to Enfield London Borough Council.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] The **Artillery Ground** in Finsbury is an open space originally set aside for archery.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] It later became a famous cricket venue, known to have staged over 200 historically important matches from 1730 to 1778.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] Today, the ground is used for military exercises, and for cricket, football, and rugby matches.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] It belongs to the Honourable Artillery Company (HAC), whose headquarters, Armoury House, overlook the ground.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] From 1498, about 11 acres (4.5 hectare) of the 23-acre (9.3 ha) Bunhill Fields were set aside for the practice of archery and 'shooting'.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] Today's 8-acre (3.2 ha) site was acquired by the Honourable Artillery Company (HAC) in 1638.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] The HAC had formerly owned a site in Bishopsgate, and this was finally sold in 1658.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] In 18th century sources, the Artillery Ground was said to lie between Chiswell Street and Bunhill Fields, the latter being a cemetery.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] According to a report dated 23 June 1722 in *The London Journal*: 'the entrance to it is by a handsome pair of iron gates to the south side next Chiswell-Street'.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] It was sometimes described in contemporary cricket reports as the 'old' Artillery Ground, which may have been a reference to its prior use for military purposes, and for other sports or entertainment.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] Crop of Christopher and John Greenwood's 8 inch-to-mile map published in 1827 from an 1830 republication (click to view all).
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] Though it was always a multi-purpose venue, the ground became famous for cricket through the mid-Georgian period.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] It was first mentioned in a cricketing context in the 1725 season.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] A further note was added to the Court Minutes on 7 October concerning abuse done to the herbage of the ground by not only the horses, but 'also by Crickett Players'.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] Despite the HAC's initial disapproval, the ground was being used for big matches only five years later.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] The earliest known historically important match there was between Middlesex and Surrey on Monday, 10 August 1730.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] The Artillery Ground soon became the feature venue for cricket in the mid-18th century; Harry Altham said it was 'indeed the precursor of Lord's'.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] Middlesex won that "inaugural" match by an unknown margin.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] Two more matches were held on the ground that season.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] Both were between London and Surrey, so they were London's earliest-known matches on what became their home ground.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] First, on Monday, 31 August, London defeated Surrey by 6 runs for a stake of 20 guineas.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] The second match was due to be played on Friday, 4 September, but no post-match report has been found.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] The ground quickly became London's first choice venue with six of their twelve home matches recorded there in 1731: three against Dartford, two against Croydon, and one against Kent.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] A report in 1732 states that the playing area was staked out and roped off.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] This practice was first reported at Kennington Common the previous year, and cricket is believed to be the first sport to enclose its venues.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] The Artillery Ground was charging spectators a two pence admission fee by the early 1740s.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] It is believed that the fee was introduced in the 1730s, cricket also being the first sport to charge for admission.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] By the 1740s, the Artillery Ground had become the sport's feature venue and for about twenty years it had a social status that only Lord's Cricket Ground has subsequently equalled.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] Single wicket was especially popular in the 1740s and huge crowds gambling huge sums of money were attracted to the ground whenever these contests took place.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] The history of the ground is coloured by references to its keepers, or lessees.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] The first known reference is in *The Craftsman* dated Sat 26 February 1732 (Julian date) re Mr Christopher Jones, Master of the Artillery Ground, at the *Pyed Horse* public house in Chiswell Street.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] The keepers were responsible for maintaining order at the ground.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] For example, Jones posted a notice in the newspapers that advertised a London v Kent match on 5 July 1733 as 'for one guinea each man with wickets to be pitched at one o'clock and the spectators to keep outside the line round the ground.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] If any persons get on the Walls [sic] they will be prosecuted as the Law directs; and the Company are desired to come through the Py'd Horse Yard, Chiswell Street'.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] Obviously, by coming through the pub, many might well stop and buy a drink.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] Jones, as the landlord, would have no objection to that.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] The most charismatic keeper was George Smith who had frequent disputes with the HAC during his tenure.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] He also had money problems and there are surviving reports of his attempts to pay off his debts by raising the ground admission and then being forced to reduce it again.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] Before the creation of the Hambledon Club in the 1760s, the Artillery Ground was the featured venue of all London cricket, but it eventually fell into disrepute because of uncontrolled gambling, and ceased to be used for top-class matches after the 1778 season.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] On 24 and 25 August 1778, it hosted London v Dartford, historically one of its main fixtures.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] The *Morning Chronicle* on Tuesday, 25 August reported that London scored over 120, and Dartford 84.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] The ground's last historically important match was England v Chertsey on 15 September 1778.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] On 15 September 1784, Vincenzo Lunardi flew a balloon from the Artillery Ground, the first such flight in England.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] The venue is now used mainly for military exercises.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] Sport still has a presence, though, as it is also used by HAC teams for cricket in the summer, and for football and rugby matches in the winter.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] Notably, the ground hosted a rugby union match between Saracens and the USA national team on 9 November 2010, which was won 20–6 by Saracens.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] The ground is also, as a source of revenue for the HAC, rented out for parties and events.
[src:artillery-ground/artillery-ground] It serves as the start area for the annual Great City Race, a 5 km run through the streets of the City of London, which is just to the south of the venue.
